text:
It would be interesting to know what happened in the Arctic during the 10,800 BCE abrupt climate change. We know there were two ice sheets - smaller Cordilleran and bigger Laurentide on North America. The Laurentide perhaps 3 - 4 km thick at some places. 

There was a paper published in Feb 2018 in The Journal of Geology about extraordinary biomass burning around 10,800 BCE. It is fascinating.

Adjusted quote: "Around 10,800 BCE, likely within the span of 21 years between 10,818 BCE and 10,797 BCE, ∼9% of Earth's terrestrial biomass, on ∼10 million km2 (area as big as the US), burned. The concentrations of soot, used to estimate the global amount of biomass burned, suggest that wildfires around 10,800 BCE consumed considerably more biomass than during the K-Pg extinction event."

If interested the links are https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/abs/10.1086/695703?journalCode=jg for part 1 and https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/abs/10.1086/695704 for part 2. 

It would be interesting to calculate how much CO2 must have been released when ∼9% of world terrestrial biomass on ∼10 million km2 burned. The wildfires on 70,000 km² in Australia this year are estimated to release about 900 million tons of CO2, which equals to double the country's total yearly fossil fuel emissions."

Perhaps CO2 released by burning of ∼9% of Earth's terrestrial biomass, on ∼10 million km2 might have contributed to melting of Cordilleran and Laurentide ice sheets? At present CO2 melts ice in Arctic, Greenlad, Antarctica so we can assume it should have been melting ice also around 10,800 BCE as well. 

There is a puzzling energy paradox. Melting of ice sheets happened during very cold period, so it should not have happened.

What mechanisms or combination of might have caused rapid melting of several kilometres thick ice sheets?

One simple physics principle is that the weight of several millions cubic kilometres of ice pushes the continent down. Heavy ice depresses the surface, at times pushing it below sea level, making the ice sheets to get in contact with warmer ocean, causing the ice sheets to retreat and stabilizing the system. Destabilize the system enough with a powerful external factor and things start moving quickly. 

Recent scientific papers start to provide more and more evidence that an external fast acting factor was in effect around 10,800 BCE. 

The paper published in March 2020 in Nature provides evidence of cosmic impact at Syria, coeval with impacts that deposited high-temperature meltglass, melted microspherules, and/or platinum at >50 sites on four continents around 10,800 BCE. Link to the article https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-020-60867-w

Impact on several kilometres thick ice sheet in Canada would not have left a permanent crater imprinted in the ground but more likely a depression filled with water which today would be in the form of a lake. 

There are several candidates for comet fragments impacts on ice sheet in Canada around 10,800 BCE. One of them possibly in Great Lakes area, perhaps the Saginaw Bay, Michigan // Lake Nippon // Manicouagan Reservoir // Gulf of Saint Lawrence // 

It is suggested it started in direction from Western coast to Eastern coast. 

It would be interesting to check the known impact craters in the world for a possible "string impacts. Just a few candidates - Rochechouart crater in France, Saint Martin crater in Manitoba, Obolon crater in Ukraine, Red Wing crater in North Dakota. If there is any researcher or enthusiast out there able to get some funding go for it.:-)

If you have not seen a string impact video please check the well-known Shoemaker–Levy 9 string impacts on Jupiter in July 1994 on BBC Studios YouTube channel https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DgOTcIfU75Y

As mentioned in the March 2020 paper in Nature (https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-020-60867-w) there might have been multiple airbursts/impacts across at least four continents. These are proposed to have resulted from a one of a series of short-period, active comets known to break up frequently and to shed dozens to thousands of fragments that are 10 to 1000 m in diameter, each capable of producing catastrophic airburst/impacts. The largest cometary debris clusters are proposed to be capable of causing thousands of airbursts within a span of minutes across one entire hemisphere of Earth. An encounter with such a million-km-wide debris cluster would be thousands of times more probable than a collision with a 100-km-wide comet or a 10-km asteroid.

text:
When invisible radiation dust fell like raindrops on May 1, 1986 in Ukraine, children walked past the reviewing stand, where Soviet leaders usually sat, but now only rows of empty chairs were in sight.

Just a few days earlier on April 26, the Chernobyl nuclear power plant located in Ukraine exploded, releasing nuclear radiation 400 times that of the Hiroshima atomic bomb dropped during World War II. It was one of the most severe catastrophes in human history. Tens of thousands of people were infected with radioactive substances for a long time, and the land was equally contaminated. Chernobyl became a deserted city overnight.

Instead of saving lives, the first thing Soviet officials did was to conceal information. The earliest news about the disaster all came from foreign media outlets. Still, the Soviet Union refused to admit that there was nuclear radiation for fear of unrest among the people. No protective masks were distributed, and books about radiation were removed from libraries. All phone calls to Chernobyl were cut off.

Local officials moved their families out of Ukraine and quickly evacuated their children while keeping the general public in the dark without any protective measures.

The parade in Ukraine went ahead under orders from above. People were told to remove the radiation-contaminated lawn with shovels, without any protective equipment, and were not told why they should do so.

Doctors were not allowed to write “acute radiation syndrome” on medical reports. And water and air were declared safe in that area.

text:
) On January 9, Libero, a nationally circulated Italian newspaper, reported the findings of an independent tribunal regarding the state-sanctioned killing of prisoners of conscience for organs in China. The newspaper article also strongly condemned the human rights crisis.

The interim judgment by the Independent Tribunal Into Forced Organ Harvesting from Prisoners Of Conscience in China (the China Tribunal) was delivered in London on December 10, 2018.


Italian media outlet Libero published an article about the London tribunal.

The article stated, “After listening to 30 witnesses for three days, from 8 to 10 December, the Chair of the tribunal, Sir Geoffrey Nice, QC, …... concluded: The Tribunal’s members are all certain – unanimously, and sure beyond reasonable doubt – that in China forced organ harvesting from prisoners of conscience has been practiced for a substantial period of time involving a very substantial number of victims."

The final judgment, which is due in spring 2019, promises details and figures. Though it carries no legal authority, it will serve as an evidence-based record that can place pressure on international organizations and raise public awareness.

Libero told its readers, “The Independent Tribunal is an independent public assembly inspired by the International Coalition to End Transplant Abuse in China (ETAC), the world's leading body to deal with the issue. Its constitution was announced in the British Parliament on the initiative of Jim Shannon, a Northern Irish member of the Democratic Unionist Party, president of the Interparliamentary Group for Religious Freedom.”

text:
@Izzy Fries  
We do what mankind has always done all through human history. We adapt.
Even if everyone in the world suddenly decided to shun technology and return to the horse & buggy or living in caves, it wouldn't make a difference. We don't give mother nature enough credit for the constantly changing earth. We have an extremely arrogant attitude to even begin to think that WE can control nature.
As someone else posted earlier, there are many factors that 'science' selectively omits in their research. 
For example- over the past several years, 'cold vents' are more commonly being accidentally discovered during oceanographic research or communication infrastructure upgrade projects in deep sea locations that emit huge volumes of hydrocarbon rich gasses such as methane and hydrogen sulfide. And the deep oceans are the least explored remaining frontier on this planet. We have no clue as to how many of these vents actually exist. No one even has an estimate  of how many could exist.
Also, as it pertains to rising sea levels... the big island of Hawaii, JUST the big island of Hawaii, expands by an average of 42 acres annually. 
How many volcanic islands are there in the world, along with those that are growing vertically from the ocean floor that continually displace sea water?
If you dump enough sand into a glass of water, eventually, it's gonna overflow.
Again, factors like these are never brought up in the climate argument. 
This planet has been through and survived cataclysmic events that dwarf whatever consequence mankind could ever create. It has always bounced back better than before, & the earth will go on by itself just fine for billions of years beyond our own existence until the sun begins to collapse and grow to the point that all the planets in the solar system will be incinerated. 
On that thought, Have a Nice Day!🙂

text:
@coryg121  
Scientists need to get paid just like everyone else. 
If they request a grant from a government agency, corporation, institution or some other entity to fund research which results in a scientific conclusion that happens to contradict the organization's agenda, that entity simply refuses to fund that research. 
When a grant is requested, the scientist(s) involved must detail the anticipated or intended findings of their research. 
Grants are far more likely to be provided which support research that agrees with the vision of that particular entity. 
Although the government still provides more than 50% of all scientific funding(through taxes from you & I), it actually provides much less funding than it did just 10 or 15 years ago, leading to increased competition between scientific research groups to obtain funding.
This results in private institutions and individual philanthropists being relied on much more than they had been in the past to provide such funding. 
Individuals and private organizations are much more likely to have biased opinions. So, of course, this bias gets carried over into scientific 'conclusions.'
Bottom line? Do your own research into the source of funding for these 'scientific findings,' as opposed to simply repeating like a parrot what the politicians are spouting.
"Question Authority."

text:
All this arrogant, platitudinous garbage is nauseating. 


NOBODY on that stage is going to eliminate the subsidization of oil and gas. 
NOBODY on that stage is going to issue an Executive Order to stop drilling or mining on public lands.


The fact that there are some listening to this that will bark and clap like an obedient little seal when they hear these lovely ear-tickling proposals is so damn disappointing. These candidates, as crazy as they sound, know better (yes, even crazy 'ol Bernie). They know that they cannot just upend our entire economy in order to placate a few small activist groups. They understand that the vastly enormous economic system we've got, imperfect as it may be, cannot simply be changed at the whim of politicians driven by their own special interest groups.


I like that we've been closing down coal power plants. I like that our dependency on those is waning. What I don't like is this stupid climate alarmism demanding that I need to stop using or doing any given thing today or else within a half dozen or so years, something bad will happen. 
Also- somebody please explain to me why it was a bad thing that we exited the Paris climate accord? Why was it so bad that we exited this non-binding resolution that did not hold anybody (except ironically the US) accountable for their actions related to the climate? This was feel-good virtue-signaling to let others know that "we care" but otherwise will not make any real changes. News flash- we don't need a stupid accord to signal to the world that we think we need to make a change for the better- lets actually make that change and suggest the rest of the world follow suit if our numbers support our actions.

They keep saying they believe in "science."
But I can't find an actual Scientist of repute who backs their claims.

I've worked with over a hundred fellow physicist (3 PhDs) Chemists, and yes, Climate Scientists.
The subject has come up with nearly every one of them, and the closest to support any of them ever offered was to say there is NO evidence to support it, but none to dispute it either, it would take decades of data-collectin to form a viable basis for the science and we were Denied the chance to obtain that.
Professors who did not support the theory without evidence, Lost tenure, grants to those who did not offer unqualified, universal support, Lost Grants.

It became clear in the immediate that if you worked in a university setting or had grants from any governing body, you had no choice but to procllaim it a certainty.
But those same scientists, in person-to-person discussion, held the opposing viewpoint.

Science... is not supposed to be subjective, let alone subject oto political whins.
Flat Eart reminds us how well that works - ith some of thegreatest minds in their fields forced to agree or diee... and many of those who arer referenced as supporting the flat-earth claims, produced written records showing that th4ey, in fact, did no such thing.

We will soon see the same with Heating Trend/Pending Ice Age/AGW/Climate Change.
And take note.
Climate change isn't even a theory.
It lacks any method of disproov.

If it gets hotter, it proves climate change.
If it gets Cooler, it proves climate change.
And if it fails to change, it proves climate change.
That is not a scientific theory, it is an assertion of idiocy.

text: Don’t be fooled by these ignorant politicians. They, for the most part, clearly don’t have very strong grasps on environmental science. We cannot just outlaw fossil fuels and expect society to not fall apart. We must first replace fossil fuels in energy production with reliable green energy such as nuclear power. Look at France, 75% of their electricity is nuclear while solar and wind are only about 2-3%. Forget the PCA, we should fix ourselves before even thinking about telling other countries what to do. We tend to jump ahead with things like electric cars but what good are they if the electricity is from fossil fuel power plants? When it comes to mining, we cannot just stop as we need those resources. Warren talked about “sustainable” mining as if that’s a thing (we mine for things that don’t replenish themselves so it is impossible to be sustainable). Instead, we need to make technological advancements like sodium (a very abundant element) ion batteries so we don’t need to mine for nearly as much lithium (a rare and toxic metal). Maybe focus on phasing out coal and oil before natural gas, which can act as a temporary main source of energy until we can reach mostly green. It seems to me most of these people are exaggerating the current state of global warming and using it as an excuse to implement their socialist policies. If the government was less of a regulation monster, private nuclear power plants could become more abundant. If a candidate truly cared about environmental issues, they’d talk about specific solutions, not regurgitated crap about solar and wind power (two very inefficient and destructive energy sources on a big scale). A big problem we face is the disappearing of the Ogallala Auqifer from us taking more water from it than is being replaced but they aren’t talking about that. Biden said cities are experiencing the worst, maybe thats because they are all run by Democrats? Warren kept referring to “colored communities”, isn’t that a little racist instead of calling them “poor”? Don’t believe these clowns, do your own research on environmental science as many people are ignorant on it. Can you (the reader) explain the actual science behind climate change? Define albedo, global warming potential, ozone (good and bad), CFCs, etc. Please watch some informational videos and documentaries so you can teach climate change deniers the real science rather than calling them idiots. For example, telling someone “the poor ice caps are melting and sea levels are rising” doesn’t prove global warming is human caused. That’s is an affect not proof. That proves nothing because without evidence by the scientific reasoning, you could argue that aliens are shining a laser at the poles. Remember that environmentalism isn’t political, it’s about life, all life. Republicans don’t hate nature, in fact more spend more time in it than Democrats I’m sure, they just don’t like big government and socialism.
